ge Steven\neon, and Herbert Baker, and the hungry\nliorde at Levi Ankeny's heels, would\never cease to assault t h is or any other\nmeasure designed to give the free, un\ncorrupted and ire iruptible citizens of\nthis state a decent amount of cvtilrol\norer their own affairs.\nThe peop e cf this state, theretore. will\nnot be surprised, shocked or fr gi.tened\nby ibe Olymi ia suit, and will ciTer no\nobjectU 'J t ucf the'aw. Ihey\nhave no favors to ask of the entmies of\nthe primary law. and ncne to grant.\nThey have a pretty f&.r idea of their po\nlitical rights, and they mean to exercise\nthem in a roat.iy fashion, and for the\nmateria' an i mora! goc<l of Washington.\n\u2014Seat'.le F. l.\nPRICES HERE AND ABROAD.\nWhile r e:e .ire rapidly alwinc\ning it is ccmicrtii;.: int,w that in tie\nPanama cans! z ce tnelr is a reduction\nin the price o: van v.- articles. This in\nteresting information is given in the\nCanal Kecord,' :L- official organ of ti.e\nIsthmian canal zone. For instance,\ngranulated sugar in rive pound sacks in\nAugust was ier.tr. now it is CO cents;\nyellow sugar was -S ceQta, now it is 3\ncents; Janiiw an cigars have fallen in\nprice frcm 15 to I) rents. Currants that\nwere 12 cents r.ow tan be obtained for 10\ncents per pound. The best grade of\nCentral American coffee, formerly 26\ncent* per found, is now 24 cents and\nanother grade that was 23 cents has\nbeen reduced to il cents per pound.\nWhy pti.es are dc<'..riing in Panama acd\nadvancing here, ti.e editor of the \"Canal\nReccri\" does not venture to say. Can\nit be possible that the sugar trust, the\ntobacco trust, and the other corporations\nthat plunc'er the j-eople of the United\nstates by virtue oi the trust-protecting\ntariff that our republican trust-'.ovir.g\npoliticians refuse to -evise, be selling\ncheaper in the canal zone to the Jamaica\nnegroes and ..ther .'creign laborer* than\nto our own v'c\" W pauseforareplv.\nT:.e C.ut cer\\.:n'y as a hard tiae o\u00a3-\nit. Hr; cne day and\nb.? b.s r. \"J .he\noat agi c: u.et\nb.u.. di*d si., Ji\u00ab: n; .r.\nTne pi evident is unsatisfied with tin\nConstitution, hut all the comfort he\nc >olil nive the Cairo, 111., people to\nhope that some time in the dim future it\nwould he amended. Incidentally Presi\ndent Koosevelt evidently takes for grant\ned that through him a new era may be\ninaugurated. Still, there is no getting\naround the f*ct that we have prospered\nfor generation\u00ae under the \"unsatlsfar\ntory\" organic law. and it require* three\nfourths of tie Mate* to amend it.\n\"Eat what you like,\" advises the\nPhiladelphia Enquirer. And >o we\nihould if the butcher, the baker and the\ncandle-ftick maker did not \u00bbhow each an\nogly and vulgar disposition to baggie\nover the price of things.\nIt is said that Mr. Roosevelt'* forth\ncoming mesf.ige to congress will he \"ex\ntremely long Well, it takes a lot of\nspace to touch up everything from na\nture faking to no' mentioning the tariff.\nThe Standard Oil cotnpan* is prepar-\ning to exploit the oil fields of J*p\u00abn. Af\nter little while, the Mikado will he in>r\nmitte.l io stand aside and let the com*\nparry run the government (or him.\nAndrew Carjieaie niav feel that lie\nshould die on the thresh Id of the poor,\nhouse, but he doesn't seem to care par\ntirnlarly, to have the tax collector help\nhim to get there.\n\"'The oil octopus should have beer\nfine l $100,000 000.\" says a contemporary,\nStill, if it wo lid only come up with\nthat $29,'.-J0.0.X). *11 would he forg'ver.\n\"Congressman Burton is still holding\non to his congressional job.\" says Tl e\nCommoner. Sire he is; a job in tl e\nhand is worth two in the bush.\nThe important question to the main\nambitious republicans is, will the presi\ndent be able to dictate his successor?\nFate of the Univene. I\nIn the universe there Is but one per\npetual and unchanging fact, and that\nIs\u2014change. Nothing stands still. Ev\nerything is moving either forward or\nbackward\u2014 from death to life, from\nchaos to order and back again to death\nand chaos, to turn aga'.u lu time to\nward life and order. And so the ever\nlasting drama goes on. Solar systems\nand sunflowers, worlds and worms,\nmust alike return to the dust from\nwhich they came. It is the law of\nchange, the endless march around the\ncircle of birth and death, death and\nbirth.\u2014New York American.\nThe Orange Tree.\nThe orange is the longest lived fruit\ntree. It begins to bear the third year i\nafter budding and for 100 years it will j\nyield abundant crops. Orange trees i\nhave been known to attain the ripe\nage of 300 years. The orange requires j\nless care and arrentioa than any other\nfruit tree. Its early growth Is rapid.\nIn the first two years it grows more j\nthan it will in the nest fifty. This re\nfers. of course, to Its height and j\nbreadth alone\u2014its fruit stems and con\nsequently its crops increase more rap\nidly after the first ten years.\nAmending His Epithet.\nFormer Congressman Johnson of la- j\ndiana in delate once called another\ncongressman an ass. This was un\nparliamentary and had to be with\ndrawn.\nMr. Johnson said. \"I withdraw the\nlanguage. Mr. Speaker, but I insist\nthat the gentleman from Illinois is out\nof order.\"\n\"How am I out of order?\" yelled the\nBan from Illinois.\n\"Probably a veterinary surgeon could\ntell you.\" retorted Johnson.\nThis was admissible on the records.\nNothing E!\u00bbe to Do.\nSeveral teachers who were assigned\nto the city playgrounds were discussing\nthe aausini and diversiSed ambitions\nof tie tots In their charge as to what\nthey hope to be when tbey \"grow up.\"\nA teacher told of one little girl who\nIn all sincerity gave her a reply that\nwas not likely to make her vain.\n\"Would you like to teach children when\nyou become a young lady?\" was the\nquestion. \"No'm.\" was the emphatic\nreply. \"What would you like to do?\"\npersisted the teacher. \"If I'm pretty\nTil be an actress.\" came the answer.\n\"But suppose you are homely?\" asked\nthe teacher. \"Well then, of course I'll\nhave to be a teacher,\" said the child.\nPhiladelphia Record.\nNot Altogether Bad.\nA policeman saw a aac acting rath\ner suspicious!j* near a Jewelry store\none evening: so. going over to him. he\ndemanded to know who the man was\nand what he wanted.\n\"I'm thinking of opening a Jewelry\nstore in this neighborhood,\" replied the\nman. \"End I'm watching to see if there\n!s much trade.\" Whereupon the po-\u00ab\niieeman went on his way. satisied.\nNext morning word was received at\nthe station house that the Jewelry store\n\u25a0had been entered and robbed during\nthe sight Th-> rxVJoenian who ha! \"c\n--costevl *he rious -*r' 5.y..! r\ndectJvt \"'le may tie a thau Lut he's\nco liar'\"\u2014Lippineotfs.\nABERDEEN HERALD, MONDAY, OCTOBER 21. I^o7\nThere Is No Financial\nPanic In Sight.\nBy LESLIE M. SHAW. Former Secretary of the Tre\u00bb\u00bbury.\nI R farms produce more than $t>.500,000.000 per an-\nOmim, and THE PROSPECT IS GOOD for an av\nerage crop. Our mines yield more than $1,500,000,-\n000 and our forests more than $1,000,000,000. And\nneither of these sources of wealth has been exhausted.\nThe output of our factories in other than food prod\nucts is approximately $12,000,000,000, and no fires have been extin\nguished.\nThe railwavs earn more than $'2,000,000,000, and THEY ARE\nALL IN SUCCESSFUL OPERATION. The payrolls of our facto\nries and railways aggregate approximately $3,500,000,000, and the\nscale of wages has not been reduced.\nIN OTHER WORDS, THE REAL SOURCES OF THE PEOPLE'S\nWEALTH HAVE NOT YET BEEN AFFECTED, AND THE ABILITY OF\nINDUSTRIAL CONCERNS TO PAY DIVIDENDS IS NOT MEASURED\nBY THE MARKET PRICE OF THEIR STOCKS.\nm\nBjr HENRY C. FRICK of the United State* Steel Corporation.\nI FIND NOTHING IN UNDERLYING CONDITIONS TO WARRANT\nTHE APPARENT GREAT LACK OF CONFIDENCE IN BUSINESS GEN\nERALLY WHICH NOW SEEMS PREVALENT. IF THERE IS ANY\nTHING TO JUSTIFY THAT FEELING IN TRADE CONDITIONS, I\nDO NOT SEE IT.\nI can understand the VAGUE, BUT REAL UN SETTLEMENT\nOF SENTIMENT created by current agitation against corporations,\nbut this is in a measure apart from real conditions and is capable of\ncorrection. 1 believe myself, and always have, in the correction of\nABUSES, WHETHER CORPORATE OR INDIVIDUAL, but I\nfeel that such care should be exercised in doing this that only the\nwrongdoer should sutfer.\nOf course where corporations are still acting outside of the law\nUNKNOWINGLY it is to be expected that they should bo set right,\nbut I am sure they can be accomplished without harm to any one and\nwithout the least injury to credit, if the situation is PROPERLY\nAND INTELLIGENTLY HANDLED bv the administration.\nBy JOSEPH G. CANNON, Speaker of the National Houm of Representative*.\nBOSH. ALL BOSH! THAT'S WHAT IT IS, THIS TALK OF\nFINANCIAL RUIN. THE COUNTRY NEVER WAS BETTER. AND I\nGUESS THESE WALL STREET FELLOWS ARE SQUEALING BE\nCAUSE THEY'VE BEEN STUNG.\nWith me it's simply a question of whether the bulls eat the bears\nor the bears eat the bulls. There happens to be A FEW MILLION\nFARMERS in this country of ours, and they are not bothering about\nthis cry of financial panic. They're busy harvesting their crops.\nNO FEAR. THE FARMERS WILL BE BUYING MORE AUTOMO\nBILES THIS FALL. AND INSTEAD OF DISASTER THERE WILL BE\nMORE REAL PROSPERITY THAN EVER BEFORE. REAL PROS\nPERITY, I SAID. NOT THE WALL STREET KIND.\nm x\nBy WILLIAM B. RIDGELY, Comptroller of the Currency.\nThe announcement made by Secretary Cortelyou of his plan for\nrelieving the strain on the money market by the deposit of govern\nment funds is VERY WISE AND TIMELY and should go very\nfar toward allaying apprehension and restoring business to its normal\ncondition.\nWHILE THE PRESENT SITUATION IS ONE REQUIRING CARE\nAND COOL HEADED. DELIBERATE ACTION. ESPECIALLY ON THE\nPART OF THE BANKS. THERE IS NO REASON AT ALL WHY THE\nDEMAND FOR LIQUIDATION SHOULD SO SPREAD AS TO PRODUCE\nANYTHING LIKE A PANIC OR COMMERCIAL CRISIS.\nThe banking condition is UXUSUALLY SOUXD, more so on\naccount of the readjustment of stock market values.\nNational Control of\nIndustry Is Inevitable.\nBy Dr. CHARLES J. BUSHNCLL. Sociologist, of Washington.\nCHE modern trust is the response under individualistic condi\ntions to the inevitable demand for a MORE UNIFIED\nAND ECONOMICAL business organization. And Social\nism itself, with ail its past faults and failures, is but the\nEL ETHER EFFORT to carrv the will of the people effectively into\nour industrial as well as our political life.\nBY ITS DEMAND THAT WE SHOULD OWN AND CONTROL\nCOLLECTIVELY WHAT WE NEED TO USE COLLECTIVELY. SOCIAL\nISM IS A PROTEST AGAINST THE THEORY THAT ALL A WORK\nINGMAN NEEDS AND WANTS IS A ROOF, A FAMILY AND A FULL\nDINNER PAIL. IT IS AN ASPIRATION FOR A FULLER AND\nNOBLER SOCIAL LIFE.\nFor one I believe that the present UNDENIABLE DECAY 01*\nDEMOCRATIC INSTITUTIONS, of government of, for and by\nthe people, is temporary and is slowly arousing a reaction which is\nbound to lead us into a finer and a broader national life, with adequate\nNATIONAL CONTROL of our great industries.\nAmerica Not the\nLand of the Free.\nBy Sir CASPAR PL'RDON CLARKE. Director of the Metropolitan Museum\nof Art. New York.\nHMERICA is not the land of liberty. Your blue ribbon law?\nthat make the temperate suffer for the intemperate are most\nTYRANNICAL. In England at least we have no laws in\nterfering with personal rights.\nTALK ABOUT OPPRESSION IN RUSSIA! WHERE WILL YOU\nFIND ANY GREATER OPPRESSION THAN IN THE STATE OF\nMAINE. WITH ITS UNJUST BLUE LAWS? FREEDOM! AMERICA\nCANNOT EOAST OF THAT.\nIt is WOMEN WHO ARE REALLY AT THE BOTTOM\nOF THESE BLUE RIBBON LAWS, these tyrannical r.--ri-i tis\nof pononft] Wh6H6V6r a woman permits her emoti ns to nm\naw?.*.* wit'.. r\" -:.t i- -lire tv ri:-.. i-* s t..;ug of\nthis kind. Women are ail right until they become FADDIS I'S.\nLittle Ethel\u2014Mamma, don't people\n1 ever pet punished when they tell the\ntruth?\nI Mamma\u2014Xo. dear. Why do you\nask?\nLittle Ethel\u2014'Cause I Just took the\nlast three tarts lu the pantry and 1\nthought I'd better tell you.\nA Howl.\nAn English duke, while being shown\n1 the collection of birds In a museum.\nasked the name of one of them.\n\"That's a howl.\" said the attendant.\nI \"A what?\" exclaimed the duke.\n\"A howl,\" repeated the man with\neven more distinctness, whereupon a\ni bystander, seeing the cause of the\nduke's mystification, said, \"Your royal\n'lghness. 'e says hit's a howl.\"\u2014Sir M.\nGrant Duff's Diary.\nA Sort of Slur.\nM I think.\" said Mrs. Comrox, firmly\ncompressing her lips, \"that we will get\nanother physician.\"\n\"The bill our present doctor Just sent\nIn was very reasonable,\" ventured lier\nhusband.\n\"That's the point. It was so small\nas to Indicate not only a low estimate\nof the value of our health, but also ail\nutter disregard of our social and finan\ncial Importance.\"\u2014Washington Star.\nThe Partner In Slander.\nHe that by crafty significations of ill\nwill doth prompt tb\u00a3 slanderer to vent\nhis poison; he that by a willing audi\nence and attention doth readily suck\nIt up or who greedily swalloweth it\ndown by credulous approbation and as\nsent; he that pleasingly relisheth and\nsmacketh at it or expresseth a delight\nful complacence therein; as he is a part\nner lu the fact, so is be a sharer In the\nguilt.\u2014lsaac Barrow.\nThe\n\"Only Indispensable Magazine\"\nIT'S THE AMERICAN MONTHLY\nREVIEW or REVIEWS\nTHIS YEAR IT IS MORE IN\nDISPENSABLE THAN EVER\nPRESIDENT ROOSEVELT says:\n\"I know thit throufh its columns titrs hive teen to me tkit I \u00bbaJ4\nnot otherwise hive had i:ctss :o; because ill earnest tsd tbovghtfol sea. eo\nminer how widely their iieis diverge, Are gives free nceraace ia iu coi^mn\"\nWE WANT AGENTS\nTO REPRESENT US IN EVERY COMMUNITY\nlarge and small, for full or spare time work. The liberal commis\nsions and cash prizes offe